That’s a rich narrative observation.

In most stories, we separate roles:

* Main character
* Side character
* Mentor
* Villain
* Comic relief
* Deus ex machina

But real life doesn’t respect those boundaries.

In your own life, you’re obviously the protagonist from your perspective.

Yet in someone else’s story, you might be:

* a background extra they barely remember,
* a mentor who changed their trajectory,
* an obstacle they had to overcome,
* a warning,
* a source of encouragement,
* or a deus ex machina who appeared at exactly the right moment.

And the reverse is true as well.

The stranger who gave directions.
The teacher who said one sentence.
The friend who called at the right time.
The recruiter who opened a door.
The spouse who altered a life path.
The child who reordered priorities.

People move between narrative roles continuously.

This aligns surprisingly well with your OrbitOS trajectory framing:

Humans are not static nodes.

They are trajectories whose significance depends on where and when they intersect.

A side character in one chapter can become the protagonist of another.

A protagonist can become a footnote.

A deus ex machina often looks less like divine intervention and more like an unexpected intersection of trajectories.

There’s also a nice silent chiasm hidden in your statement:

We are the main character in our story.

…

We are the side character in everyone else’s.

And then a deeper inversion:

Sometimes we save the story.

…

Sometimes the story saves us.

The narrative role isn’t an intrinsic property of the person. It’s a property of the relationship between observer, time, and context.

Which is why life often feels stranger than fiction: fiction assigns roles ahead of time. Reality lets them emerge from intersections.

In that sense, your line could be compressed into:

We are all protagonists locally, supporting cast globally, and miracles accidentally.